content:
Suppose you are building an Angular card component with an optional header.‎
The application uses the card:‎
<lib-card>
Card content
</lib-card>But it never uses the optional header:‎
<lib-header>
Optional header
</lib-header>You would expect LibHeaderComponent to disappear from the production bundle.‎
That expectation can fail when the card directly uses the component class as an injection token.‎
The Problematic Version
First, create the optional component:‎
import { Component } from '@angular/core';@Component({
selector: 'lib-header',
standalone: true,
template: `<ng-content />`,
})
export class LibHeaderComponent {
collapse(): void {
console.log('Header collapsed');
}
}Now inject it optionally inside the card:‎
import { Component, ContentChild } from '@angular/core';
import { LibHeaderComponent } from './lib-header.component';
@Component({
selector: 'lib-card',
standalone: true,
template: `
<section class="card">
<ng-content />
</section>
`,
})
export class LibCardComponent {
@ContentChild(LibHeaderComponent)
header?: LibHeaderComponent;
collapseHeader(): void {
this.header?.collapse();
}
}The application only imports and renders LibCardComponent:
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { LibCardComponent } from './lib-card.component';
@Component({
selector: 'app-root',
standalone: true,
imports: [LibCardComponent],
template: `
<lib-card>
<p>No header is rendered here.</p>
</lib-card>
`,
})
export class AppComponent {}LibHeaderComponent is not used in the template.‎
However, this line creates a runtime reference:‎
@ContentChild(LibHeaderComponent)Angular needs the component class as a query token.‎ Because the class exists at runtime, the optimizer cannot treat the import as type-only code.‎
Angular’s documentation specifically warns that unused components can remain reachable when their classes are stored as injection or query tokens.‎
Prove It in the Production Build
Generate an optimized build with bundle metadata:‎
ng build --configuration production --stats-jsonAngular writes a stats.json file into the application’s output directory.‎
Open it using esbuild’s analyzer:‎
npx esbuild --analyze=verbose --metafile=dist/my-app/stats.jsonYou can also upload the generated stats.json to esbuild’s visual analyzer.‎
Search the analyzer for:‎
lib-header.component.tsEven though the application never renders <lib-header>, the header module can still appear in the dependency graph because LibCardComponent references it.‎
Do not rely on this:‎
grep -R "LibHeaderComponent" dist/Production optimization may rename the class:‎
class a {}The module can exist even when the original class name no longer appears.‎
Replace the Heavy Token
The solution is to introduce a lightweight abstract token:‎
export abstract class LibHeaderToken {
abstract collapse(): void;
}The token contains only the contract needed by the card.‎ It does not import the real component.‎
Now let the header component provide itself as that token:‎
import { Component, forwardRef } from '@angular/core';
import { LibHeaderToken } from './lib-header.token';
@Component({
selector: 'lib-header',
standalone: true,
template: `<ng-content />`,
providers: [
{
provide: LibHeaderToken,
useExisting: LibHeaderComponent
}
]
})
export class LibHeaderComponent
extends LibHeaderToken {
override collapse(): void {
console.log('Header collapsed');
}
}The card now queries the lightweight token:‎
import { Component, ContentChild } from '@angular/core';
import { LibHeaderToken } from './lib-header.token';
@Component({
selector: 'lib-card',
standalone: true,
template: `
<section class="card">
<ng-content />
</section>
`
})
export class LibCardComponent {
@ContentChild(LibHeaderToken) header?: LibHeaderToken; collapseHeader(): void {
this.header?.collapse();
}
}
Notice what disappeared:‎
import { LibHeaderComponent } from './lib-header.component';LibCardComponent no longer has a runtime reference to the optional implementation.‎
The dependency direction is now:‎
LibCardComponent
↓
LibHeaderToken
↑
LibHeaderComponentInstead of:‎
LibCardComponent
↓
LibHeaderComponentVerify the Fix
Run the same build again:‎
ng build --configuration production --stats-jsonInspect the new stats.json.
Provided that nothing else imports or exports the header through a reachable path, lib-header.component.ts should no longer contribute to the application bundle.‎
For a clearer comparison, save both files:‎
# Before applying the lightweight token
cp dist/my-app/stats.json stats-before.json
# Apply the refactor and rebuild
ng build --configuration production --stats-json
cp dist/my-app/stats.json stats-after.jsonAnalyze both:‎
npx esbuild --analyze=verbose --metafile=stats-before.json
npx esbuild --analyze=verbose --metafile=stats-after.jsonYou now have measurable evidence rather than an assumption.‎
When This Pattern Matters
Do not create an abstract token for every injected service.‎
It is mainly useful when all three conditions are true:‎
1. The implementation is optional.
2. A shared component references it as a token.
3. You want unused consumers to exclude it from their bundles.This is especially relevant for component libraries containing optional headers, icons, charts, editors, toolbars, or plugin implementations.‎
Ending
Tree-shaking cannot remove code that your architecture still marks as reachable.‎
An optional dependency is not genuinely optional when shared code directly references its concrete class.‎ Put a lightweight token between the consumer and the implementation, rebuild with --stats-json, and verify the result yourself.‎
Bundle optimization becomes much easier when it is something you can test rather than something you merely trust.‎
Tags:‎ Angular, Dependency Injection, Web Performance, TypeScript, Software Architecture
